$\qquad
\begin{align}
(x+2)^2(x+1)(x-1)(x-2)^2
\end{align}
$

Factors correspond to $x$‑intercepts, and since the equation is fully factored, we can see all the $x$‑intercepts.

$\qquad
\begin{align}
-2 \cdot -1 \cdot 1 \cdot 2 =& 4
\end{align}
$

The product of the distinct $x$‑intercepts of the graph is $4$.

The quadratic equation tells us that one of the solutions to this equation is:

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{k+\sqrt{k^2-4(1)\left(-\dfrac13\right)}}{2(1)} =\dfrac{k+\sqrt{k^2+4\left(\dfrac13\right)}}{2}
\end{align}$

This must be equal to the solution given in the question.
